<subSubSection lastPageId="37" lastPageNumber="807" pageId="35" pageNumber="805" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="35.[160,1156,1093,1395]" box="[160,294,1093,1118]" pageId="35" pageNumber="805">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,294,1093,1118]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="805">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[160,1156,1093,1395]" pageId="35" pageNumber="805">
A small species of the genus (SVL 87.3–130.3, x = 116.1, n = 15) with a total length usually about 
<quantity box="[326,424,1163,1187]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="35" pageNumber="805" unit="mm" value="300.0">300 mm</quantity>
, tail more than half again longer than the SVL in adult males. Head narrow (particularly in males), occipital scale lacking. Nasal scale not convex, smooth, below the canthus rostralis, often not visible from above. Ear openings as large as eyes, with the tympanum conspicuous. No nuchal crest. Dorsal scalation heterogeneous, matrix scales keeled and mucronate, irregularly intermixed with enlarged keeled and mucronate scales of two sizes, but not as distinct as in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gunther" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[1037,1150,1336,1360]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Acanthocercus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="35" pageNumber="805" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gregorii">
<emphasis box="[1037,1150,1336,1360]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="805">A. gregorii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Vertebral scales enlarged, becoming continuously smaller to the flanks, not as distinct as
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[160,1157,1506,1713]" pageId="35" pageNumber="805">
64 = northern slopes Ngorongoro; 65 = Olduvai Gorge, 
<collectingRegion box="[672,735,1506,1526]" country="Tanzania" name="Arusha" pageId="35" pageNumber="805">Arusha</collectingRegion>
; 66 = Serengeti, Naabi Gate; 67 = Kakitumba; 68 = Ntaruka; 69 = 
<collectingRegion box="[345,401,1533,1553]" country="Uganda" name="Kibale" pageId="35" pageNumber="805">Kibale</collectingRegion>
; 70 = Mpanga; 71 = Ntaruka?; 72 = Lake Nasho; 73 = Mpanga?; 74 = 
<collectingRegion box="[1053,1152,1533,1553]" country="Burundi" name="Bujumbura Mairie" pageId="35" pageNumber="805">Bujumbura</collectingRegion>
; 75 = Digg 
<emphasis box="[259,263,1560,1580]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="805">’</emphasis>
s Farm nr. Amoressa; 76 = Sanga; 77 = only coordinates; 78 = 
<collectingRegion box="[880,940,1560,1580]" country="Tanzania" name="Tabora" pageId="35" pageNumber="805">Tabora</collectingRegion>
Udjidji; 79 = Kakoma; 80 = Ukimbu; 81 = Nguru Mountains; 82 = Bagamoyo; 83 = Kilosa; 84 = Karema; 85 = Kakokwe; 86 = Tukuyu; 87 = Rutenganio; 88 = Mwaya; 89 = Matema; 90 = Utengule; 91 = Ilolo; 92 = Uhehe; 93 = Liwale; 94 = Manengue; 95 = Kilwa; 96 = Arba Minch; 97 = Lake Shala; 98 = Mahal Uonz; 99 = Masai 
<collectingRegion box="[160,204,1667,1687]" country="Tanzania" name="Mara" pageId="35" pageNumber="805">Mara</collectingRegion>
NP; 100 = Lyanza; 101 = Kikambo; 102 = Sanga; 103 = Metemna; 104 = NE Songea District; 105 = 
<collectingRegion box="[1085,1152,1667,1687]" country="Tanzania" name="Singida" pageId="35" pageNumber="805">Singida</collectingRegion>
; 106 = 
<collectingRegion box="[221,276,1693,1713]" country="Mozambique" name="Niassa" pageId="35" pageNumber="805">Niassa</collectingRegion>
Game Reserve.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174483" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5174483" box="[160,1011,1253,1276]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174483/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="806" startId="36.[160,225,1253,1276]" targetBox="[178,1138,142,1222]" targetPageId="36">
<paragraph blockId="36.[160,1011,1253,1276]" box="[160,1011,1253,1276]" pageId="36" pageNumber="806">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,265,1253,1276]" pageId="36" pageNumber="806">Figure 15.</emphasis>
Holotype (ZMB 23906) of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Klausewitz" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[534,771,1253,1276]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Acanthocercus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="36" pageNumber="806" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kiwuensis">
<emphasis box="[534,771,1253,1276]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="806">Acanthocercus kiwuensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from Kissenji, Rwanda.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="36.[160,1156,1329,1700]" pageId="36" pageNumber="806">
in other species. Body scales in 73–96 rows [up to 116 mentioned by (
<bibRefCitation author="Sternfeld R" box="[980,1148,1329,1353]" pageId="36" pageNumber="806" refId="ref21426" refString="Sternfeld R. 1912. Wissenschaftliche Ergebnisse der Deutschen Zentral-Afrika Expedition 1907 - 1908, unter Fuhrung A. Friedrichs, Herzogs zu Mecklenburg. Klinkhard und Biermann, Leipzig. IV. Zoologie II. Lfg. Reptilia; p. 197 - 279 [the volume was published in parts from 1911 to 1913 but this part was published in 1912]." type="book" year="1912">Sternfeld 1912</bibRefCitation>
) around midbody (x = 83.6, n = 29) and 55–77 (x = 62.7, n = 15) longitudinal rows along the vertebrae. Ventral scales smooth and small, as large as the medium-sized dorsal scales, in 57–74 (x = 63.9, n = 15) longitudinal rows. Gular scales small, keeled, and exposed, slightly smaller than the ventral scales. Males with two to three continuous rows (x = 2.2, n = 18) and a total number of 16–28 precloacal pores (x = 20.2, n = 18), absent in females. Dorsal scales of the tail base not as distinctly swollen as in e.g. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gunther" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[160,273,1572,1596]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Acanthocercus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="36" pageNumber="806" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gregorii">
<emphasis box="[160,273,1572,1596]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="806">A. gregorii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith, Illustrations" authorityYear="1849" box="[314,433,1572,1596]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Agama" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="36" pageNumber="806" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="atricollis">
<emphasis box="[314,433,1572,1596]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="806">A. atricollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but distinct from other scales of the tail.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[160,1156,1329,1700]" lastBlockId="37.[160,1155,142,270]" lastPageId="37" lastPageNumber="807" pageId="36" pageNumber="806">
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Klausewitz W" box="[347,544,1607,1631]" pageId="36" pageNumber="806" pagination="157 - 174" refId="ref20422" refString="Klausewitz W. 1957. Eidonomische Untersuchungen uber die Rassenkreise Agama cyanogaster und Agama atricollis. Die Unterarten von Agama atricollis [Eidonomic studies about the species complex of Agama cyanogaster and Agama atricollis. The subspecies of Agama atricollis]. Senckenb Biol. 38: 157 - 174." type="journal article" year="1957">Klausewitz (1957)</bibRefCitation>
this species has a very characteristic coloration: adult males with a yellowish green to greenish blue head, throat whitish to blue, body deep blue with some pale blue dots, base and first third of the tail yellow, followed by yellowish green second third and a brownish tip. 
<bibRefCitation author="Sternfeld R" box="[766,951,142,166]" pageId="37" pageNumber="807" refId="ref21426" refString="Sternfeld R. 1912. Wissenschaftliche Ergebnisse der Deutschen Zentral-Afrika Expedition 1907 - 1908, unter Fuhrung A. Friedrichs, Herzogs zu Mecklenburg. Klinkhard und Biermann, Leipzig. IV. Zoologie II. Lfg. Reptilia; p. 197 - 279 [the volume was published in parts from 1911 to 1913 but this part was published in 1912]." type="book" year="1912">Sternfeld (1912)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned male specimens from ‘Kissenje’ [=Gisenyi] having the entire body blue and the tail uniform olive-yellow. However, the non-nuptial coloration shows a pattern of yellow spots and stripes on the body as well.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="807" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="37.[160,1155,329,492]" box="[160,300,329,354]" pageId="37" pageNumber="807">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,300,329,354]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="807">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[160,1155,329,492]" pageId="37" pageNumber="807">
Since its description (
<bibRefCitation author="Klausewitz W" box="[408,593,364,388]" pageId="37" pageNumber="807" pagination="157 - 174" refId="ref20422" refString="Klausewitz W. 1957. Eidonomische Untersuchungen uber die Rassenkreise Agama cyanogaster und Agama atricollis. Die Unterarten von Agama atricollis [Eidonomic studies about the species complex of Agama cyanogaster and Agama atricollis. The subspecies of Agama atricollis]. Senckenb Biol. 38: 157 - 174." type="journal article" year="1957">Klausewitz 1957</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Klausewitz" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[616,751,364,388]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Acanthocercus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="37" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kiwuensis">
<emphasis box="[616,751,364,388]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="807">A. kiwuensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had been considered restricted to the mountainous areas around Lake Kivu (
<collectingCountry box="[632,723,399,423]" name="Rwanda" pageId="37" pageNumber="807">Rwanda</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[780,832,399,423]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="37" pageNumber="807">DRC</collectingCountry>
). Herein, it is recognized as a wide-ranging species from Lake 
<collectingRegion box="[531,579,433,457]" country="Democratic Republic of the Congo" name="Sud-Kivu" pageId="37" pageNumber="807">Kivu</collectingRegion>
in the south to central 
<collectingCountry box="[854,942,433,457]" name="Uganda" pageId="37" pageNumber="807">Uganda</collectingCountry>
and north-eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[160,208,468,492]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="37" pageNumber="807">DRC</collectingCountry>
in the north (
<figureCitation box="[370,477,468,492]" captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="38.[160,225,1079,1102]" captionTargetBox="[178,1138,142,1048]" captionTargetId="figure-42@38.[178,1138,142,1048]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="Figure 16. Distribution of Acanthocercus kiwuensis and A. ugandaensis. The numbers refer to the specific localities." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174485" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174485/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="807">Figure 16</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[160,1155,550,645]" box="[160,405,550,575]" pageId="37" pageNumber="807">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,405,550,575]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="807">Habitat and ecology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[160,1155,550,645]" pageId="37" pageNumber="807">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Klausewitz" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[160,432,586,610]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Acanthocercus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="37" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kiwuensis">
<emphasis box="[160,432,586,610]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="807">Acanthocercus kiwuensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been found on trees in savannah woodland, but also on man-made structures (e.g. houses, old walls) near cities and towns (EG, pers. obs.).
</paragraph>
